You need two things: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` and **`BackButtonBehavior`** on the page.

### 1. Guard navigation in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back navigation
    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop &&
        Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page &&
        page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();   // user chose "Stay" — cancel navigation

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

> **Key:** You must call `GetDeferral()` before any `await`, then `deferral.Complete()` when done. Without it, the navigation completes before your async dialog returns.

### 2. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

```csharp
// In your ViewModel
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    // This triggers a Pop, which hits your OnNavigating guard
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

### How it works together

| User action | What happens |
|---|---|
| Taps **Cancel** button | `CancelCommand` → `GoToAsync("..")` → `OnNavigating` fires → dialog shown |
| Android/iOS back gesture | `OnNavigating` fires directly → dialog shown |
| User picks **"Stay"** | `args.Cancel()` stops navigation |
| User picks **"Discard"** | Navigation proceeds normally |

The `HasUnsavedChanges` property is yours to manage — set it `true` when form fields change, `false` after saving.
